06546nam a22008295i 9781554584178DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545841787 a10.51644/97815545841782doi  a(DE-B1597)667652  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9188.2.M55bC84 2012eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04aC810.9/822300aCultural Grammars of Nation, Diaspora, and Indigeneity in Canada /ced. by Melina Baum Singer, Sophie McCall, Christine Kim. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransCanada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tI Present Tense -- tDiaspora and Nation in Métis Writing -- tCanadian Indian Literary Nationalism? -- tBreaking the Framework of Representational Violence -- t“Grammars of Exchange” -- tII Past Participles -- tUnhomely Moves -- tAsian Canadian Critical Practice as Commemoration -- tDiasporic Longings -- tAfro-Caribbean Writing in Canada and the Politics of Migrant Labour Mobility -- tIII Future Imperfect -- tRacialized Diasporas, Entangled Postmemories, and Kyo Maclear’s The Letter Opener -- tUnderwater Signposts -- t“Phoenicia ≠ Lebanon” -- tWord Warriors -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the TransCanada Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultural Grammars of Nation, Diaspora, and Indigeneity in Canada considers how the terms of critical debate in literary and cultural studies in Canada have shifted with respect to race, nation, and difference. In asking how Indigenous and diasporic interventions have remapped these debates, the contributors argue that a new “cultural grammar” is at work and attempt to sketch out some of the ways it operates. The essays reference pivotal moments in Canadian literary and cultural history and speak to ongoing debates about Canadian nationalism, postcolonalism, migrancy, and transnationalism. Topics covered include the Asian race riots in Vancouver in 1907, the cultural memory of internment and dispersal of Japanese Canadians in the 1940s, the politics of migrant labour and the “domestic labour scheme” in the 1960s, and the trial of Robert Pickton in Vancouver in 2007. The contributors are particularly interested in how diaspora and indigeneity continue to contribute to this critical reconfiguration and in how conversations about diaspora and indigeneity in the Canadian context have themselves been transformed. Cultural Grammars is an attempt to address both the interconnections and the schisms between these multiply fractured critical terms as well as the larger conceptual shifts that have occurred in response to national and postnational arguments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aMinoritieszCanadaxSocial conditions. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPolitical Science: Globalization. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBaum Singer, Melina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapperdoni, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCho, Lily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEigenbrod, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmberley, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagan, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel